{"questionId":"9074774","questionHtml":"<p>Gases in the atmosphere are compounds of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mtext>C</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>6</mn><mn>12</mn></mmultiscripts></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mtext>H</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mmultiscripts></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mtext>O</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>8</mn><mn>16</mn></mmultiscripts></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mtext>N</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>7</mn><mn>14</mn></mmultiscripts></math>.</p>\n<p>Four of these gases are CO<sub>2</sub>, N<sub>2</sub>O, CH<sub>4</sub> and H<sub>2</sub>O. A pure sample of each gas is produced. Each sample has the same mass.</p>\n<p>Which sample contains the greatest number of molecules?</p>\n<p><br>A.&nbsp; N<sub>2</sub>O</p>\n<p>B.&nbsp; H<sub>2</sub>O</p>\n<p>C.&nbsp; CO<sub>2</sub></p>\n<p>D.&nbsp; CH<sub>4</sub></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>D</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9074774","referenceCode":"22N.1.HL.TZ0.11","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Gases in the atmosphere are compounds of C612, H11, O816 and N714. Four of these gases are CO2, N2O, CH4 and H2O. A pure sample of each gas is produced. Each sample has the same ma","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"11","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 3: Thermal physics","3.2 – Modelling a gas","Core","Topic 3: Thermal physics"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}